text_answer.content:
Outlay is great example of how not fully exploring the related words can be meaningless. It's not a word I use or was even really familiar with previously, so I had to dig a bit into its particular nuance and I discovered it makes sense that I'd never have a need to use it as I've never encountered the need to put an initial or significant investment of capital into something: "The initial outlay for the new equipment was quite high." Simply saying "money paid out or spent; an expenditure" suggests that I could go to the grocery store and expect an outlay (expenditure) at the register. Except that's not how it's used. No student is going to walk away from this unit knowing how to use outlay correctly.
As I said in my email "Giving a student a definition, one word that clearly aligns with the definition, and three choices that clearly don't, doesn't really help them dig into how the meaning functions differently from the words around it." In fact, I'd argue it's gotten worse since a student could walk away thinking outlay is an interchangeable synonym when in reality it has a fairly narrow usage.

Not sure expendably is a word and, if it is, it's more related to the idea of something that is seen as unnecessary rather than related the usage of finances or resources. This relates to Working with Word Forms 5.

text_answer.content:
The basic point I'm about to make is that the second definition is never used in the way the sentence is written.
Manifestation as a word is sort of weird since its usage doesn't really match the definition and its synonyms.
There are, ultimately, three major definitions. The first one listed is the most common, which in my mind is synonymous with 'example.' The second is actually not included (for good reason) and is related to supernatural/occult phenomena. The third (which is the second one on the page) is used more as an umbrella term for events related to demonstrations of power and purpose (Merriam-Webster's definition).
Examples of definition 1 used in a sentence:
"Her frequent headaches were the first manifestation (example) of a more series health condition."
"Cox said the project is a manifestation (example) of all of those goals."
"To me, this is a manifestation (example) of one of our deepest fears, the fear of being wrong (or the need to be right)."
For the second definition:
"We organized meetings, parades, and other such manifestations (similar events)." - This is taken from Merriam-Webster's page.

I'm going to skip going over the Defining Synonyms and Antonyms here as there's too much that needs to be fixed.

text_answer.content:
Indoctrinate is a weird word. Like, the definition is basically correct here, but it's also sort of incorrect? The reason I bring this up is because Merriam-Webster lists educate and teach as top synonyms, but colloquially both suggest a certain amount of critical thinking - which this definition explicitly does not include. I think ultimately this definition is a little too heavy handed with the bias aspects.

Mixed opinions on indoctrinative. I ultimately don't think it's a word since, when I Googled it, the first source related to a dictionary or thesaurus was powerthesaurus.org. The first two responses were a journal article on jstor from 1996 and another article on a .gov site related to the US Department of Education.
Indoctrinatingly is in the same boat as its top response is spellcheck.net followed by a bunch of social media posts and/or reviews.
